;\"><strong>ATS Integrated Logistic Support services include but are not limited to the following:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"color: #000000;\">\r\n	<li>System Configuration Identification &amp; Validation\r\n- System Diagrammatics\r\n- Configuration Item / Technical Information (CI-TI) Database Development\r\n- System Failure Analysis\r\n- Preventative Maintenance / Supportability Analysis\r\n- Ship Change Document (SCD)/Non-SCD Identification and Tracking</li>\r\n	<li>Integrated Logistic Support Troubleshooting and Repair</li>\r\n	<li><a style=\"color: #8a2216;\" href=\"http://atsid.com/solutions/lifecycle-support-solutions/ils-support-training/ils-training-services\">Technical &amp; Logistics Training</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style=\"color: #8a2216;\" href=\"http://atsid.com/solutions/lifecycle-support-solutions/ils-support-training/ils-systems-support\">Integrated Logistic Support Systems Support</a>(e.g. ICAPS, CDMD-OA, OMMS-NG, etc.)</li>\r\n	<li>Business Process and Workflow Automation</li>\r\n	<li>DoDAF Modeling Support</li>\r\n	<li>Software/Database Development</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\"><a style=\"color: #8a2216;\" href=\"http://atsid.com/forms/contact-us?interest=lifecycle-support-solutions\">\r\n</a><a title=\"Contact Us\" href=\"http://dev.atsid.com/meet-ats/contact-us/\">Contact ATS today</a>to learn more about our Integrated Logistic Support services and other logistics solutions.</p>','ILS Support & Training','','inherit','open','open','','293-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 21:34:06','2014-07-18 21:34:06','',293,'http://dev.atsid.com/2014/07/18/293-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(300,3,'2014-07-18 21:38:11','2014-07-18 21:38:11','[caption id=\"attachment_301\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"213\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-301\" src=\"http://dev.atsid.com/wp-content/uploads/classroom_training.jpg\" alt=\"Delivering comprehensive ILS Training to ship maintenance personnel\" width=\"213\" height=\"142\" /> Delivering comprehensive ILS Training to ship maintenance personnel[/caption]\r\n<h3>Preparing the support community to maintain the finest fleet in the world</h3>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS is well positioned to design, develop and implement any type of ILS training program our customers may require -- and we dont have to start from scratch. Our extensive practical experience working with all elements of logistics at all levels, coupled with our demonstrated ability to develop and deliver ILS training, is quite frankly unmatched anywhere in the industry.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS is well positioned to design, develop and implement any type of ILS training program our customers may require -- and we dont have to start from scratch. Our extensive practical experience working with all elements of logistics at all levels, coupled with our demonstrated ability to develop and deliver ILS training, is quite frankly unmatched anywhere in the industry.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">The Navys Integrated Logistics Support (ILS) system is a complex collection of organizations and activities that produce various pieces of the ILS puzzle. This shore-based system is not well defined or integrated, and is relatively fluid in both structure and processes. Most fleet personnel know very little about the ILS system or its products, largely because the system is not discussed or taught in any meaningful way in most training schools and there is little opportunity to learn system details when assigned to either ship or shore duty. This lack of education, understanding and experience in the details of the ILS system extends to engineering, operations, maintenance, and even supply personnelboth officer and enlisted. Some have some exposure to pieces of the system but few have any real in-depth experience with the full spectrum of ILS processes and products. This is unfortunate since the lack of onboard logistics support has repeatedly been identified by both the Chief of Naval Operations (as well as the GAO) as the single biggest contributing factor to poor system sustainability and operational readiness.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS recognized this problem years ago when its founder started using shipboard technicians to develop and implement early Integrated Logistics Overhauls (ILO) processes in the Pacific Fleet. In order to teach sailors how to analyze and correct ILS deficiencies it was first necessary to define the processes through which each element of logistics support was produced. This then became the basis for training sailors how to troubleshoot and fix ILS problems for their systems during the ILO process.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">The ILS system training and outfitting processes developed during the 4-year Pacific Fleet ILO development process was the basis for the formation of ATS in 1980. The Navy wanted to expand the ILO effort Navy-wide and ATS was created and tasked to assist in that effort. This tasking included development of detailed procedures for conducting ILOs and providing both classroom and on-the-job training to start-up ILO sites in the Atlantic Fleet. ATS used this same ILS system theory and system supportability analysis processes to train its new employees, most of which were experienced maintenance technicians representing the full spectrum of ship systems. ATS has maintained its in-house training program to reflect the many changes in ILS products and processes that have occurred over the past 30 years. This training program continues to be the primary means of converting newly hired shipboard maintenance (and supply) technicians into qualified maintenance/logistics support analysts. It is also the basis for development of various training programs we have developed for our customers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">After training start-up sites in basic ILO procedures, ATS was tasked to design and develop a comprehensive training course for ship maintenance and supply personnel in the use and maintenance of all ILS products during the ships operating cycle. ATS developed a two-week course called the Integrated Shipboard Maintenance Support (ISMS) course which was designed for senior ship maintenance and supply personnel. The course included one week of system theory and another week of practical ILS troubleshooting and repair procedures using real problems in real products on real ships. Using four 2-man travelling instructor teams, the highly successful ISMS courses were taught to thousands of sailors and officers on all types of ships in all major home ports for a period of about 5 years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">As an outgrowth of the ISMS training program, ATS conceived, designed and developed the shipboard Maintenance Support Center (MSC) concept for aircraft carriers. The MSC concept focused ISMS training on 12-16 maintenance and supply technicians assigned full-time to the newly created MSC, rather than trying to train literally hundreds of work center personnel on CV/CVNs. The MSC concept was implemented on the first carriers in the mid-80s and ATS continues to provide on-site and at-sea training and technical assistance to MSCs on all matters related to ILS problems on all aircraft carriers, in both the Pacific and Atlantic fleet. This training includes specialized training in computer-based shipboard maintenance and supply systems, including OMMS-NG, MODES and R-Supply as well as off-ships systems such as CDMD-OA, COSAL, WSF, CSMP and many others.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS has also developed and delivered ISMS-like training for shipyard material management personnel called Shipyard Material Identification Course (SMIC). SMIC designed to teach shipyard civil service personnel how to use various ILS products to better identify and order material requirements for complex overhauls. SMIC training was provided to hundreds of shipyard personnel in all naval shipyards for a period of several years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\"><a title=\"Contact Us\" href=\"http://dev.atsid.com/meet-ats/contact-us/\">Contact ATS today</a>to learn more.</p>','ILS Training Services','','publish','open','open','','ils-training-services','','','2014-07-18 21:38:11','2014-07-18 21:38:11','',293,'http://dev.atsid.com/?page_id=300',0,'page','',0),(301,3,'2014-07-18 21:37:11','2014-07-18 21:37:11','','classroom_training','Delivering comprehensive ILS Training to ship maintenance personnel','inherit','open','open','','classroom_training','','','2014-07-18 21:37:11','2014-07-18 21:37:11','',300,'http://dev.atsid.com/wp-content/uploads/classroom_training.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(302,3,'2014-07-18 21:38:11','2014-07-18 21:38:11','[caption id=\"attachment_301\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"213\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-301\" src=\"http://dev.atsid.com/wp-content/uploads/classroom_training.jpg\" alt=\"Delivering comprehensive ILS Training to ship maintenance personnel\" width=\"213\" height=\"142\" /> Delivering comprehensive ILS Training to ship maintenance personnel[/caption]\r\n<h3>Preparing the support community to maintain the finest fleet in the world</h3>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS is well positioned to design, develop and implement any type of ILS training program our customers may require -- and we dont have to start from scratch. Our extensive practical experience working with all elements of logistics at all levels, coupled with our demonstrated ability to develop and deliver ILS training, is quite frankly unmatched anywhere in the industry.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS is well positioned to design, develop and implement any type of ILS training program our customers may require -- and we dont have to start from scratch. Our extensive practical experience working with all elements of logistics at all levels, coupled with our demonstrated ability to develop and deliver ILS training, is quite frankly unmatched anywhere in the industry.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">The Navys Integrated Logistics Support (ILS) system is a complex collection of organizations and activities that produce various pieces of the ILS puzzle. This shore-based system is not well defined or integrated, and is relatively fluid in both structure and processes. Most fleet personnel know very little about the ILS system or its products, largely because the system is not discussed or taught in any meaningful way in most training schools and there is little opportunity to learn system details when assigned to either ship or shore duty. This lack of education, understanding and experience in the details of the ILS system extends to engineering, operations, maintenance, and even supply personnelboth officer and enlisted. Some have some exposure to pieces of the system but few have any real in-depth experience with the full spectrum of ILS processes and products. This is unfortunate since the lack of onboard logistics support has repeatedly been identified by both the Chief of Naval Operations (as well as the GAO) as the single biggest contributing factor to poor system sustainability and operational readiness.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS recognized this problem years ago when its founder started using shipboard technicians to develop and implement early Integrated Logistics Overhauls (ILO) processes in the Pacific Fleet. In order to teach sailors how to analyze and correct ILS deficiencies it was first necessary to define the processes through which each element of logistics support was produced. This then became the basis for training sailors how to troubleshoot and fix ILS problems for their systems during the ILO process.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">The ILS system training and outfitting processes developed during the 4-year Pacific Fleet ILO development process was the basis for the formation of ATS in 1980. The Navy wanted to expand the ILO effort Navy-wide and ATS was created and tasked to assist in that effort. This tasking included development of detailed procedures for conducting ILOs and providing both classroom and on-the-job training to start-up ILO sites in the Atlantic Fleet. ATS used this same ILS system theory and system supportability analysis processes to train its new employees, most of which were experienced maintenance technicians representing the full spectrum of ship systems. ATS has maintained its in-house training program to reflect the many changes in ILS products and processes that have occurred over the past 30 years. This training program continues to be the primary means of converting newly hired shipboard maintenance (and supply) technicians into qualified maintenance/logistics support analysts. It is also the basis for development of various training programs we have developed for our customers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">After training start-up sites in basic ILO procedures, ATS was tasked to design and develop a comprehensive training course for ship maintenance and supply personnel in the use and maintenance of all ILS products during the ships operating cycle. ATS developed a two-week course called the Integrated Shipboard Maintenance Support (ISMS) course which was designed for senior ship maintenance and supply personnel. The course included one week of system theory and another week of practical ILS troubleshooting and repair procedures using real problems in real products on real ships. Using four 2-man travelling instructor teams, the highly successful ISMS courses were taught to thousands of sailors and officers on all types of ships in all major home ports for a period of about 5 years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">As an outgrowth of the ISMS training program, ATS conceived, designed and developed the shipboard Maintenance Support Center (MSC) concept for aircraft carriers. The MSC concept focused ISMS training on 12-16 maintenance and supply technicians assigned full-time to the newly created MSC, rather than trying to train literally hundreds of work center personnel on CV/CVNs. The MSC concept was implemented on the first carriers in the mid-80s and ATS continues to provide on-site and at-sea training and technical assistance to MSCs on all matters related to ILS problems on all aircraft carriers, in both the Pacific and Atlantic fleet. This training includes specialized training in computer-based shipboard maintenance and supply systems, including OMMS-NG, MODES and R-Supply as well as off-ships systems such as CDMD-OA, COSAL, WSF, CSMP and many others.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS has also developed and delivered ISMS-like training for shipyard material management personnel called Shipyard Material Identification Course (SMIC). SMIC designed to teach shipyard civil service personnel how to use various ILS products to better identify and order material requirements for complex overhauls. SMIC training was provided to hundreds of shipyard personnel in all naval shipyards for a period of several years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\"><a title=\"Contact Us\" href=\"http://dev.atsid.com/meet-ats/contact-us/\">Contact ATS today</a>to learn more.</p>','ILS Training Services','','inherit','open','open','','300-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 21:38:11','2014-07-18 21:38:11','',300,'http://dev.atsid.com/2014/07/18/300-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(303,3,'2014-08-27 17:09:46','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<h3>ATS Provides Fleet Support and Assistance During Technology Insertion</h3>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">ATS is prepared to provide a variety of program and fleet support services during technology insertion. Following the US Navy guidelines illustrated within the SHIPMAIN process, we plan and coordinate ship grooms, providing data collection, evaluation, training and equipment assistance. We augment the skill and resources of the fleet to provide both onboard and land based technical support to resolve system problems and collect system data to analyze and provide recommen