e%3Darticle%2Ctitle%2Curl&amp;pc=men&amp;pub=&amp;ssl=0&amp;sid=53c9b1ea47fe971e&amp;srpl=1&amp;srcs=1&amp;srd=1&amp;srf=1&amp;srx=1&amp;ver=300&amp;xck=0&amp;xtr=0&amp;og=url%3Dhttp%253A%252F%252Fatsid.com%252Fhistory%26title%3DHistory%26type%3Darticle%26site_name%3DATS&amp;aa=0&amp;csi=undefined&amp;rev=1405430506&amp;ct=1&amp;xld=1&amp;xd=1\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\"></iframe></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div id=\"block-system-main\" class=\"block block-system block-main block-system-main odd block-without-title\">\r\n<div class=\"block-inner clearfix\">\r\n<div class=\"content clearfix\"><article id=\"node-basic-page-165\" class=\"node node-basic-page node-published node-not-promoted node-not-sticky author-ebendesign odd clearfix\">\r\n<div class=\"content clearfix\">\r\n<div class=\"field field-name-field-supporting-image field-type-image field-label-hidden clearfix\">\r\n<div class=\"field-items\">\r\n<div class=\"field-item even\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</article></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>ATS is Founded</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nApplied Technical Systems was founded in 1980 by Rick Leenstra upon his retirement from the Navy. Prior to his retirement, Leenstra led an effort to implement the Integrated Logistics Overhaul Program (ILO) fleet wide. The program was formally commissioned as a Navy-wide maintenance improvement effort. Leenstra decided to settle down in Washington with his family upon retirement after 23 years of enlisted and commissioned service. Leenstra was asked by a senior NAVSEA official coordinating the ILO efforts to continue implementing the ILO effort as a contractor. Leensstra agreed and formed ATS as a means to work with the Navy to fully implement the ILO program.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_280\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\"]<a href=\"http://dev.atsid.com/wp-content/uploads/ADMJackWilliams_1.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-280 size-thumbnail\" src=\"http://dev.atsid.com/wp-content/uploads/ADMJackWilliams_1-150x142.jpg\" alt=\"ADMJackWilliams_1\" width=\"150\" height=\"142\" /></a> ADM Jack Williams, then Chief of Naval Material teaching COSAL[/caption]\r\n<h3>ATS legacy with Admiral J. G. Jack Williams, USN</h3>\r\n<div>Admiral Jack Williams graduated from the Naval Academy in 1946 and reported to a destroyer as Gun Boss. After completing submarine training he served on USS Pompodon (SS-486) and USS Stickelback (SS-415). He later commanded USS Sterlet (SS-392) and after nuclear power training commanded USS Haddo (SSN-604) and USS Daniel Webster (SSBN-626). After a tour as Director of Training for Naval Reactors, he assumed duties as Force Material Officer (N4) for Commander Submarine Forces, Atlantic. He then took command of Submarine Squadron 16 in Rota, Spain. Upon completion of that tour he was selected for Rear Admiral and subsequently served as Naval Attach to the Turkish Navy. Later he commanded Submarine Group Five in San Diego. Upon promotion to Vice Admiral he served as Deputy Commander, U.S. Pacific Fleet and then as Vice Chief of Naval Operations for Submarine Warfare. In 1981 he was promoted to Admiral and assigned duties as Chief of Naval Material. Admiral Williams retired from the Navy in 1983 and returned to his boyhood home in Illwaco, Washington.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nIn 1984 he joined ATS as a director and eventually assumed the position of Chairman of the Board, which he held until his unexpected death in 1991. During this period Admiral Williams was instrumental in creating the Naval Undersea Museum in Keyport, served as President of the Northwest Chapter of the Naval Submarine League, and was a key player in helping ATS develop configuration-based lifecycle logistics support solutions for both submarines and surface ships.\r\n<h3>A heritage in solving complex data problems</h3>\r\n<div>Several years before XML became a de facto standard, ATS realized the need for a hierarchical, self-describing, data modeling and storage technology. ATS developed the Contiguous Connection Model (CCM) technology to facilitate rapid information retrieval, enhance data navigation and visualization, and promote knowledge discovery. This patented technology (US Patent #s 5,303,367 and 5,555,409), which was revolutionary for its time, automatically correlates hierarchical data, models it, and stores it in expandable name/value pairs. CCM goes much furtherit creates a complete new hierarchical structure for each and every data point, with the data point as the root. These \"inversions\" are permanently stored and can be intuitively browsed using our powerful visualization tools.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nCCM was the pre-cursor to REGGAE, patented under 8,069,188 which is a core component of the ATS Cloud Analytical Platform. REGGAE is an innovative cellular-like data model to describe and relate complex data structures, perform distributed data analytics and find similar data based on like connections and attributes. The invention in this latest patent provides a means to easily discover behaviors and patterns among seemingly unrelated data. For example, a retail store can easily analyze its customer behaviors to determine which products are more suitable for different demographics. There are numerous applications in healthcare, evidence discovery, threat intelligence, etc.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','History','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 23:53:17','2014-07-18 23:53:17','',72,'http://dev.atsid.com/2014/07/18/72-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(372,3,'2014-07-18 23:53:46','2014-07-18 23:53:46','<div id=\"block-views-ats-timeline-block\" class=\"block block-views block-ats-timeline-block block-views-ats-timeline-block odd block-without-title\">\r\n<div class=\"block-inner clearfix\">\r\n<div class=\"content clearfix\">\r\n<div class=\"view view-ats-timeline view-id-ats_timeline view-display-id-block year view-dom-id-5d1b52c4e86dc69850b26766195f258a\">\r\n<div class