 both flush and fix any type of life cycle support data problemthrough automated updates back to source systems.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"attn\">Finding and fixing the root cause of these problems is what ATS does best.</span></p>\r\n<p>ATS can help you outline a sustainment strategy/plan to deliver increased readiness and availability.<strong> <a href=\"http://atsid.com/contact-us?interest=msat-demo\">Contact ATS</a> </strong>todayto learn more about our in-depth Maintenance and Readiness Support Services.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The data that defines the Configuration Items (CI) that collectively constitute ship systems and the seemingly endless array of Technical Information (TI) that define or drive life cycle support requirements for these CI are extremely complex and dynamic. Unfortunately, this interdependent data is typically maintained in disparate databases with little if any life cycle interaction. Engineering data soon gets out of sync with maintenance data and the various elements of logistics get out of sync with both engineering and maintenance dataand all get out of sync with the actual system configuration.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The sole function of lifecycle logistics support products is to facilitate efficient and effective execution of system maintenance functions. The only way to truly measure the effectiveness of these products (and the processes behind them) is to analyze actual system failures to see how well the logistics support system supported the maintenance action.</p>\r\n<p>Failure analysis goes beyond looking at CASREP data. In order to get a true picture of whats failing, logistics support analysts need to take a close look at all maintenance actions to determine exactly what failed, what logistics support was required to restore the system, and whether or not that support was readily identifiable and available to the system technician.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3></h3>','Maintenance and Supportability Analysi